rootNodes.name: Developers Intro
rootNodes.config:
{ 
"title": "Intro for Developers",
 "summary": "This tutorial walks you through the technical aspects of Superalgos so that you may take advantage of the infrastructure in place as efficiently as possible.",
 "subTitle": "",
 "gif": "",
 "image": "",
 "definition": "",
 "bulletListIntro": "I will cover the following topics:",
 "bulletArray": 
[
 ["Architecture:", "Architectural overview of the system."], 
["Client:", "How the Client is organized."], 
["Frontend:", "How the UI works."] 
],
 "paragraph1": "",
 "callOut": "",
 "externalLink": ["", ""],
 "paragraph2": "",
 "note": "This is a 3-year-old project that has pivoted a few times to reach its current state of development. It was initially intended for trading bots competitions and is now focused on crypto-trading automation in general. The main technical pivot occurred when we decided to depart from a centralized cloud-based app, to a decentralized network of nodes.",
 "tip": "",
 "important": "",
 "warning": "", 
 "position": "",
 "slider": "toTop",
 "pressButton": "",
 "documentationURL": "" 
}

tutorialTopics.name: Architecture
tutorialTopics.config:
{ 
"title": "System Architecture",
 "summary": "Superalgos is essentially a Node.js application + a Web App.",
 "gif": "",
 "image": "",
 "definition": "",
 "bulletListIntro": "The overall idea is that Superalgos runs at users' machines. Advanced users may deploy multiple Superalgos nodes in a LAN and distribute tasks easily. In the current version, these nodes are not ready to be exposed to the Internet. Someday they will, and eventually, they will be able to provide services to other users. These services may include:",
 "bulletArray": 
[
 ["Data Products:", "Pre-calculated indicators or studies."], 
 ["Backtest Execution:", "To scale testing capabilities."], 
["Live Trading Execution:", "Only if trusted entities emerge."], 
["Data Processing Execution:", "External data processing power."] 
],
 "paragraph1": "",
 "callOut": "",
 "externalLink": ["", ""],
 "paragraph2": "",
 "note": "",
 "tip": "",
 "important": "",
 "warning": "", 
 "position": "",
 "slider": "toTop",
 "pressButton": "",
 "documentationURL": "" 
}

tutorialTopics.name: Client
tutorialTopics.config:
{ 
"title": "Client",
 "summary": "The Client has two main components: The Client and the Task Server. When you run the app, what you are running are the Client. An instance of the Task Server is put to run once a user decides to run a task.",
 "gif": "",
 "image": "",
 "definition": "",
 "bulletListIntro": "",
 "paragraph1": "Once the services at the Client are running, the default web browser is called with the URL of the local machine so that it may load the UI and let users interact with the system.",
 "callOut": "",
 "externalLink": ["", ""],
 "paragraph2": "",
 "note": "The system holds all of its data and logs in the installation folder. The system does not modify—in any way—anything outside the installation folder. Deleting this folder completely removes Superalgos from the computer.",
 "important": "",
 "warning": "", 
 "position": "",
 "slider": "toTop",
 "pressButton": "",
 "documentationURL": "" 
}

tutorialTopics.name: Client
tutorialTopics.config:
{ 
"title": "Client",
 "summary": "Is a collection of servers running on a single Node.js process.",
 "gif": "",
 "image": "",
 "definition": "",
 "bulletListIntro": "The servers are:",
 "bulletArray": 
[
 ["Web Server:", "Serves all the JS files that form the User Interface to the browser."], 
["Web Sockets Server:", "Enables the UI to reach the Client via WS."], 
["Events Server:", "Enables the UI to communicate with the Task Manager Server and all of the Task Servers process instances via events over WS."] ,
["Task Manager Server:", "Manges Task Servers processes based on users commands."]
],
 "paragraph1": "",
 "callOut": "",
 "externalLink": ["", ""],
 "paragraph2": "",
 "note": "All of these servers are custom built—in-house—for Superalgos. We prefer to build on top of rock-solid, widely-used, low-level libraries only, like WS, for instance.",
 "tip": "",
 "important": "",
 "warning": "", 
 "position": "",
 "slider": "toTop",
 "pressButton": "",
 "documentationURL": "" 
}

tutorialSteps.name: Web Server
tutorialSteps.config:
{ 
  "subTitle": "Web Server",
 "gif": "",
 "image": "",
 "definition": "The Web Server has two main goals: it serves all the JS files that form the Web App and all the data files to be plotted at the charts to the browser that is running the UI.",
 "bulletListIntro": "The complete list Web Server uses is:",
 "bulletArray": 
[
 ["JS Files:", "Enables the Web App to run on a browser."], 
["JSON Data Files:", "Allows the UI to access data to plot."], 
["Images:", "Images used on the UI are served from the Web Server."] ,
["JSON Workspaces Files:", "Allow users to create definitions on different Workspaces."] ,
["JSON Plugin Files:", "Files that are automatically included on Workspaces for convenience."] 
],
 "paragraph1": "",
 "callOut": "",
 "externalLink": ["", ""],
 "paragraph2": "",
 "note": "",
 "tip": "",
 "important": "",
 "warning": "", 
 "position": "",
 "slider": "toTop",

}

tutorialSteps.name: Web Sockets Server
tutorialSteps.config:
{ 
  "subTitle": "Web Sockets Server",
 "gif": "",
 "image": "",
 "definition": "This is a simple implementation of a web sockets server. It essentially allows the UI or any of the other services to communicate with the Events Server via WS.",
 "bulletListIntro": "",
 "paragraph1": "The system does not allow different processes to talk to each other via WS. All they can do is talk to the Events Server to subscribe to events or to emit events.",
 "callOut": "",
 "externalLink": ["", ""],
 "paragraph2": "",
 "note": "The Web Socket Server enables this indirect communication mechanism between all processes and the UI running on a single machine, as well as communication between processes running on different machines.",
 "tip": "",
 "important": "",
 "warning": "", 
 "position": "",
 "slider": "toTop",
 "pressButton": "",
 "documentationURL": "" 
}

tutorialSteps.name: Events Server
tutorialSteps.config:
{ 
  "subTitle": "Events Server",
 "gif": "",
 "image": "",
 "definition": "The Events Server provides the communication model between processes and the UI. It essentially allows any entity inside each process to create a system-wide event handler and allow any other entity inside a process (or the UI) to subscribe or emit events at that event handler.",
 "bulletListIntro": "Events-based communication happens between:",
 "bulletArray": 
[
 ["UI and Task Manager:", "To run and stop Task Server processes."], 
["Task Server and UI:", "To get online feedback of what is going on at the Task Server, to display relevant status info at the UI."]
],
 "paragraph1": "",
 "callOut": "",
 "externalLink": ["", ""],
 "paragraph2": "",
 "note": "The communication between the UI and the Web Server is HTTP only.",
 "tip": "",
 "important": "",
 "warning": "", 
 "position": "",
 "slider": "toTop",
 "pressButton": "",
 "documentationURL": "" 
}

tutorialSteps.name: Task Manager Server
tutorialSteps.config:
{ 
  "subTitle": "Task Manager Server",
 "gif": "",
 "image": "",
 "definition": "The Task Manager Server is a simple server to manage the execution of Task Servers Node.js processes. It keeps track of all the instances running at any point in time and allows the UI to decide when to run more instance or stop any of those running.",
 "bulletListIntro": "The Task Manager Server provides the following commands to the UI:",
 "bulletArray": 
[
 ["Run Task:", "Used to run a new task, spawns a Node.js fork process where a Task Server is run."], 
["Stop Task:", "Sends a fork-process-message to the Task Server instance that needs to stop."], 
["Task Status:", "Tells the caller if the Task Id provided corresponds to a running task or not."] 
],
 "paragraph1": "",
 "callOut": "",
 "externalLink": ["", ""],
 "paragraph2": "",
 "note": "",
 "tip": "",
 "important": "",
 "warning": "", 
 "position": "",

 "documentationURL": "" 
}

{
    "title": "Task Server",
    "summary": "The Task Server is a Node.js fork process of Client that receives the definition of the Task that needs to run from the UI . ",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "",
    "definition": "",
    "bulletListIntro": "The definition includes:",
    "bulletArray": [
        [
            "Bot to run:",
            "The bot might be a Sensor Bot, an Indicator Bot or a Trading Bot."
        ],
        [
            "Processes to run:",
            "Each bot definition may have one or more bot processes. "
        ]
